Script: 2-path
#!/bin/bash
export PATH="$PATH:/action"

Explanation:
First line: #!/bin/bash - Shebang specifying Bash interpreter

Second line: export PATH="$PATH:/action" - Adds /action to the end of the current PATH

How it works:
PATH is a reserved environment variable that contains directories where the shell looks for executables

$PATH undergoes parameter expansion and is replaced with the current PATH value

"$PATH:/action" creates a new string with /action appended to the current PATH

export makes the change available to child processes (covered in Package 3)

Demonstration:
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ echo $PATH
/home/julien/bin:/home/julien/.local/bin:/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin:/usr/games:/usr/local/games:/snap/bin
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ source ./2-path 
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ echo $PATH
/home/julien/bin:/home/julien/.local/bin:/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin:/usr/games:/usr/local/games:/snap/bin:/action

Key concepts demonstrated:
PATH variable - Shell searches directories in order from left to right

Exporting variables - Making changes available to the environment

Parameter expansion - Using $PATH to reference the current value

Appending to PATH - Using :$PATH syntax to add to the end

Since /action is added to the end of PATH, the shell will look in all other directories first before checking /action, making it the last directory searched for programs.

